5  Mapping data

Another way one can visualize data is through mapping. Maps are super useful for identifying spatial patterns, trends, and outliers. They also help the audience to understand your data and your analysis.

5.1 Reading Shapefiles

Shapefiles store geographic locations and, sometimes, other attributes (data) associated with these locations. In this lecture, we will use a shapefile that stores polygons - specifically, census tracts within Chicago-IL (download that here). The .shp portion contains the geometry data (census tract), and we use the rgdal package to read this file. Apply readOGR() to the chi_homic.shp:

#install.packages("rgdal)
library(rgdal)
chi_homic<-readOGR("chi_homic.shp")
OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
Source: "/Users/marcelinoguerra/Desktop/R-guide-book/chi_homic.shp", layer: "chi_homic"
with 801 features
It has 6 fields

The class of this object is SpatialPolygonsDataFrame. It contains polygons (Chicago census tracts) and data relative to each location. Use the View() function and check all the components of chi_homic.

class(chi_homic)
[1] "SpatialPolygonsDataFrame"
attr(,"package")
[1] "sp"

The simple plot() function gives you an idea about how the shape looks like:

plot(chi_homic)

Use@data to separate the dataframe from the polygons:

#View(chi_homic@data)

5.2 Mapping data with tmap

Using the tmap package, one can easily make static quantile maps. For instance, to see the total population in 2020 within Chicago census tracts:

library(tmap)
tm_shape(chi_homic)+
tm_borders(lwd = 2, col = "white", alpha = .4)+
tm_polygons("total_popE", 
            style="quantile", 
            alpha=0.7,
            palette = "YlOrRd", 
            title="Total Population (2020)")+
tm_legend(legend.title.size = 1.7,
          legend.text.size = 1, 
          legend.position = c("left", "bottom"))

You can define the breaks you want to display in the map using breaks=c() instead of style="quantile". It is also possible to move the mapâ€™s legend (for instance, top right instead of top left). This time, we use homicide rates in 2020 instead of the total population:

tm_shape(chi_homic)+
tm_borders(lwd = 1.2, col = "white", alpha = .6)+
tm_polygons("ratehomic", 
  breaks=c(0,0.1,0.5,1.5,3, 5.2), 
  palette = "YlOrRd",
  title="Homicide per 1,000 people (2020)")+
  tm_legend(legend.title.size = 1.2,
            legend.text.size = .8,outside=TRUE)+
  tm_basemap(server="OpenStreetMap",alpha=0.5)

Besides, maps can be viewed interactively by switching to view mode, using the command tmap_mode("view"):

tmap_mode("view")

tm_shape(chi_homic)+
tm_borders(lwd = 1.2, col = "white", alpha = .6)+
tm_polygons("ratehomic", 
  breaks=c(0,0.1,0.5,1.5,3, 5.2), 
  palette = "YlOrRd",
  title="Homicide per 1,000 people (2020)")+
  tm_legend(legend.title.size = 1.2,
            legend.text.size = .8,outside=TRUE)

For interactive maps, there are different types of basemaps. Letâ€™s try the â€œOpenStreetMapâ€:

tm_shape(chi_homic)+
  tm_borders(lwd = 1.2, col = "white", alpha = .6)+
  tm_polygons("ratehomic",
        breaks=c(0,0.1,0.5,1.5,3, 5.2), 
        palette = "YlOrRd",
        title="Homicide per 1,000 people (2020)")+
tm_legend(legend.title.size = 1.2,
          legend.text.size = .8,outside=TRUE)+
tm_basemap(server="OpenStreetMap",alpha=0.5)

One additional advantage of interactive maps is that you can show more information in your map by choosing variables using popu.vars(). Finally, if you want to change the colors, choose a different palette (here you have some options)

tm_shape(chi_homic)+
tm_borders(lwd = 1.2, col = "white", alpha = .6)+
tm_polygons("ratehomic", 
        breaks=c(0,0.1,0.5,1.5,3, 5.2), 
        palette = "Purples",
        title="Homicide per 1,000 people (2020)", 
popup.vars=c("Homicide per 1,000"="ratehomic",
      "Total Population"="total_popE", 
      "Total Number of Homicides"="totalhomic" ))+
tm_legend(legend.title.size = 1.2,
          legend.text.size = .8,outside=TRUE)+
tm_basemap(server="OpenStreetMap",alpha=0.5)

5.3 Exercise: Mapping Income within Chicago Metro Area

One of the predictions of the Monocentric City Model with two income groups with the same commuting costs is that the high-income residents will live in the suburbs, and the low-income group will locate in the city center. Here you have data about 2,210 census tracts within the Chicago-Naperville-Elgin (IL-IN-WI) metro area. The information about median household income (income) and poverty levels (perc_pov) comes from the American Community Survey 2015-19.

Using tmap, show the spatial distribution of these two variables within the Chicago metro to check whether the modelâ€™s prediction matches the reality.
